## Global and Regional Video Asset Sourcing Strategies

The creation of high-engagement factual content, as exemplified by channels like The Maryos Verse, is fundamentally dependent on a rich and varied visual library . The research goal requires identifying free, non-professional, and region-specific clip sources from China, Indonesia, the USA, and India. Analysis reveals that a robust and cost-effective strategy involves a hybrid approach, combining vast global public domain libraries with curated collections from academic, governmental, and grassroots regional archives. This method not only provides access to a massive volume of general footage but also allows creators to inject unique cultural and contextual authenticity into their videos, which is crucial for standing out in a crowded digital landscape.

The foundation of any creator's asset library rests upon large-scale, reliable, and legally clear video repositories. These platforms serve as the primary source for acquiring royalty-free HD and 4K footage across a wide array of topics relevant to the "amazing facts" niche, including science, technology, animals, and experiments [[214,215,222]]. Pixabay stands out as a premier resource in this category, offering over 5.7 million media assets, including more than 118,000 free science videos and over 443 clips related to learning Chinese [[53,64,214]]. Its reliability and sheer scale make it an indispensable starting point for sourcing foundational visual elements for any script [[53,207]]. Similarly, Pexels provides another highly dependable source of free stock video footage, with thousands of new 4K videos added daily, covering subjects from scientific innovation to close-up shots of electronic devices [[160,217,220]]. Beyond these mainstream platforms, the concept of Open Educational Resources (OER)—learning materials in the public domain or under permissive licenses—is a "lesser-known" avenue that aligns perfectly with a grassroots ("jugaad") content creation philosophy [[169,243]]. Institutions like MIT OpenCourseWare offer free access to lecture notes, exams, and videos from actual courses, providing a potential goldmine of high-quality, academically sound visuals that can add a layer of credibility and uniqueness to a video [[165]]. These OER materials represent a deeper cut, less saturated by commercial content, and directly tap into the wealth of knowledge produced by leading academic institutions.

To move beyond generic visuals and incorporate local flavor, creators must look to region-specific archives within the specified countries. In China, significant efforts have been made to democratize education through initiatives like the China Open Resources for Education (CORE) consortium, which has made 750 courses available from 222 universities [[245]]. While primarily text-based, these platforms may contain video lectures or supplementary materials that could be repurposed for short-form content. Furthermore, Tencent Cloud, a major technology player, offers developer-focused tools like a User Generated Short Video SDK, suggesting a vibrant ecosystem of user-created content that may be accessible for reuse [[1]]. Academic publications from Chinese institutions often feature technical diagrams and animations related to cutting-edge research in fields like deep learning and radar systems, which can be adapted for explaining complex technological concepts [[17,19]]. Platforms like The Public Domain Review are described as hidden gems containing copyright-free works from around the world, which could include culturally relevant Chinese media [[129]].

For Indonesian content, the National Library of Indonesia offers a direct source of culturally specific introductory videos, forming a valuable archive for historical and cultural topics [[187]]. More immersive resources, such as the Virtual Museum of Indonesian National History, provide authentic historical footage that can bring stories to life in a way that generic stock footage cannot [[186]]. The success of TikTok creators like @hariwindaru ("Cerita Nusantara"), who produce engaging videos about local heroes like "SAWUNGGALING," demonstrates a strong audience interest in such content and validates the strategy of sourcing from regional cultural repositories [[84]]. Studies on user-generated translation activities on Chinese social media platforms reveal that sites like Bilibili host a vast amount of user-generated content, which can be a source for raw, unedited clips [[127]]. Browser extensions designed to enhance the Bilibili experience, such as Awesome Bilibili Extra, can help navigate this content-rich environment [[149]]. In the USA, beyond public domain libraries, there are opportunities in government and public sector releases. For example, the scraping of the eCourts India website to build a functional web application demonstrates the potential for finding structured, reusable data and media in public domains [[183]]; similar opportunities likely exist across various US federal and state agencies. Creators can also leverage browser extensions to download public domain or Creative Commons licensed videos from other YouTube channels, tapping into a vast pool of existing content [[111,263]]. Finally, for India, the State of the Education Report for India 2024 highlights the connections between culture, art, and education, pointing towards a national repository of knowledge that may be available in video format [[79]]. The localization of online courses, such as MOOCs, to be more culturally responsive suggests the availability of video components tailored t