## Real-Time and Post-Creation Captioning Automation

Dynamic, rapidly appearing captions are a signature element of The Maryos Verse channel's aesthetic, enhancing viewer engagement and reinforcing the fast-paced delivery of information [[162]]. Achieving this effect does not require expensive, specialized hardware; instead, a combination of native operating system features, browser extensions, and dedicated software provides a suite of powerful, free tools for both real-time and automated post-production captioning. These tools enable creators to not only make their content more accessible to a wider audience, including those who are deaf or hard of hearing, but also to amplify the core message of their videos [[74,279]].

For capturing live-action footage or recording gameplay commentary, where real-time transcription is essential, the best solution is often already built into the user's device. Microsoft Edge, the default browser on Windows, includes a powerful "Live Captions" feature that is completely free and requires no configuration [[22]]. This tool automatically generates subtitles for any audio playing on the screen, whether it's a YouTube video, a Netflix stream, a Zoom meeting, or a Twitch broadcast [[22]]. It can be activated with a simple keyboard shortcut and displays as a floating window, making it ideal for recording sessions where the creator needs to see the captions simultaneously with the action. This functionality helps ensure that spoken words are accurately captured during the initial recording phase, providing a clean transcript for later refinement. This native solution is far more convenient and cost-effective than third-party alternatives and perfectly serves the needs of a grassroots content creator.

Beyond real-time capture, a plethora of automated tools can generate accurate captions for pre-recorded videos. VEED.io is a prominent online tool that boasts a 99.9% accuracy rate in its automatic caption generator [[58]]. It supports over 125 languages and allows users to export the generated captions as standard subtitle files (like SRT) for easy import into video editing software, or directly embed them into the video file [[124,161]]. Canva also integrates a powerful auto-captioning feature that enhances accessibility and appeal by adding correctly generated captions to videos [[59]]. For creators who prefer desktop applications, Submagic offers a streamlined workflow where a video file can be dropped onto the program to instantly generate a transcript with synchronized captions, saving hours of manual work [[296]]. Other tools like Transkriptor are also noted for their high accuracy, reaching up to 99%, and supporting over 100 languages, making them suitable for a wide range of international content [[307]].

In addition to standalone captioning generators, browser extensions provide a versatile and immediate way to add subtitles to any video content viewed online. Immersive Translate is a particularly useful extension that can detect audio on any webpage and generate real-time AI subtitles, even for videos that do not have them [[38]]. If a video lacks captions, the extension first uses AI to transcribe the audio and then translates it if needed, providing a seamless multilingual viewing experience [[308]]. DeepL for Chrome offers similar functionality, focusing on providing real-time, accurate translations for web pages, which can be useful for understanding foreign-language content before adapting it for a video [[255]]. For downloading subtitles from platforms like YouTube, extensions such as Subtitle Downloader for Netflix, YouTube & More provide support for numerous languages, including Bahasa Indonesia, Malay, and Bengali, facilitating the acquisition of existing subtitles for reference or reuse [[234]]. These browser-based tools demonstrate how modern web technologies can be leveraged to automate what was once a labor-intensive task, empowering creators to focus on storytelling rather than technical execution.

